snippet.title: Nearly 100,000 homes remain unsold in the first three months of 2025
snippet.description:
Malaysia may be heading for another property glut ‚Äî nearly 100,000 residential units remain without buyers in the first quarter of 2025.

According to Napic, homes priced between RM200,001 and RM300,000 make up the largest share of unsold stock, followed by those in the RM300,001‚ÄìRM400,000 range.

Most of these units are still under construction or not yet built, giving developers time to secure buyers ‚Äî but if left unchecked, they risk becoming abandoned.

12,498 new residential units were launched nationwide, but only 11 per cent were sold within three months.

Condominiums and apartments dominate the overhang, with over 13,000 units unsold.

The median house price is RM359,000, but the national median household income is just RM6,338 ‚Äî far below what‚Äôs needed to afford a typical home.

Selangor, Perak, and Johor lead in unsold units under construction, with thousands more already approved but not yet built.

Housing Minister Nga Kor Ming declined to comment, saying he would respond after verifying the data with his ministry.

snippet.description:
A social media influencer has been arrested by the Malaysian Maritime Enforcement Agency (MMEA) after placing a car on a platform at sea for a photoshoot.

The arrest took place during Operation Iman near Pulau Bidong, about 16 nautical miles off Kuala Terengganu.

Authorities say the stunt, carried out on a platform towed by a passenger boat, violated the Merchant Shipping Ordinance 1952 (MSO).

A second escort boat without a valid license was also detained.

In total, 12 Malaysians ‚Äî including the influencer, crew, and passengers were taken into custody.

Both boats and those detained were brought to the Terengganu State Maritime Jetty for investigation.

The case is being investigated under the Merchant Shipping Ordinance for license violations, operating without a valid license, and illegal towing activities.

snippet.description:

The prime minister, who is the current Asean chairman, said Indonesian President Prabowo Subianto had told him during a meeting in Beijing that the situation in Jakarta was improving.

snippet.description:

The accused, Wong Chong Loong, Sim Jia Ie and Ngoh Tian Song, all painters by trade, pleaded not guilty to two charges read out by the court interpreter before Judge Osman Affendi Mohd Shalleh.

In the second charge, they allegedly robbed a 68-year-old woman using the same weapons, stealing her multi-purpose vehicle and cash.

snippet.title: Abu Sahid's wife claims trial to RM67 million money laundering charge
snippet.description:
The wife of Maju Holdings Sdn Bhd director Tan Sri Abu Sahid Mohamed today claimed trial at the Sessions Court to a charge of money laundering involving almost RM67.14 million allegedly linked to the proposed Putrajaya-KLIA (MEX II) highway project.

Puan Sri Noor Azrina Mohd Azmi,48, who is also a director of Maju Holdings, was accused of receiving the funds into her personal bank account from Abu Sahid's account, believed to be proceeds from illegal activities.

Clad in a black blazer and a blue shirt, Noor Azrina entered her plea before judge Rosli Ahmad.

Lawyer Datuk Hisyam Teh Poh Teik stood next to Noor Azrina, who was in the dock, as the charge was read out to her.

She was alleged to have committed the offence at a bank in Bukit Tunku between March 6, 2017 and Nov 27, the same year.

The charge, under Section 4(1)(b) of the Money Laundering, Anti-Terrorism Financing and Proceeds of Unlawful Activities Act (AMLA), is punishable under Section 4(1). It carries a maximum 15-year jail term and a fine of not less than five times the amount of proceeds from illegal activities or RM5 million, whichever is higher.

Deputy public prosecutor Datuk Ahmad Akram Gharib, who appeared with Mohamad Fadly Mohd Zamry, informed the court that both parties had agreed on bail being set at RM500,000 with one surety and for her passport to be impounded.

snippet.title: Ex-Mex II director pleads not guilty to forgery charges involving RM314mil
snippet.description:
A former director of Mex II Sdn Bhd, a subsidiary of Maju Holdings Sdn Bhd, pleaded not guilty in the Sessions Court today to 17 counts of document forgery involving false claims amounting to RM314,486,100, allegedly linked to the proposed construction of the Putrajaya-KLIA (MEX II) highway project.

Datuk Yap Wee Leong, 68, who appeared in court wearing a lime green batik shirt, entered his plea before Judge Rosli Ahmad.

The charges involve the alleged submission of falsified progress claims for various works, including site clearance, temporary works, earthworks, geotechnical works, drainage, and pavement, purportedly for the MEX II highway project, which was planned to run from the Putrajaya Interchange to KLIA under Maju Holdings.

The offences were allegedly committed between June 2017 and April 2018 at Maju Holdings Sdn Bhd's office at Maju Tower in Jalan Sultan Ismail.

Yap was accused of dishonestly using the claims as genuine despite knowing they were forged.

The charges under Section 471 of the Penal Code are punishable under Section 465 which provides a maximum of two years imprisonment, a fine or both upon conviction.

Deputy public prosecutor Datuk Ahmad Akram Gharib, who appeared alongside Mohamad Fadhly Mohd Zamry, proposed a bail of RM1 million.

snippet.title: When the pen was mightier than the sword
snippet.description:
Sixty-eight years ago, Malaya was still under British rule. Life was constrained, yet the spirit to determine our own destiny burned ever stronger. While many nations achieved independence through bloodshed and war, our homeland chose a different path‚Ä¶ the path of the pen.

On Jan 18, 1956, Tunku Abdul Rahman led the Malayan delegation to London, alongside Tun Tan Cheng Lock and Tun V.T. Sambanthan, representing the unity of the country's different communities. At Lancaster House, they negotiated with the British. The talks were not easy, but with patience and wisdom, a historic date was agreed upon: Aug 31, 1957.

Here lies the symbolism of our independence. Not with the sound of gunfire, not with the spilling of blood, but through the stroke of ink. The pen became the weapon, and the document signed in London was what opened the door to our nation's freedom.

And on the morning, Aug 31, 1957, thousands gathered at Merdeka Stadium. As the Union Jack was lowered and the Jalur Gemilang was hoisted for the very first time, tears of joy streamed down the faces of the people. That was the moment a free nation was born.

The New Straits Times Press (NSTP), one of Malaysia's oldest newspaper companies, was an important witness to this history. Report after report, printed with ink on newspaper pages, became a crucial source of information for the people. From the news of the London talks to the declaration of independence, everything was immortalised through ink and the printing press.

Today, NSTP, under the umbrella of Media Prima, continues to carry that trust. It delivers news accurately, fosters public discourse, and connects the old generation with the new. From printed newspapers to digital platforms, the role of ink ‚Äî whether as fluid or pixels ‚Äî remains the same: to write the history of a nation.

Behind every news story, there is a journalist's sacrifice. There is an effort to unite a people. There is a reminder that this independence was not free. It came as a result of unity, consensus, and the courage of leaders and a people who chose the negotiating table.

On this National Day, let us remember the choice our nation made. We are free because our leaders chose to spill ink, not blood. And that ink continues to flow through the pages of our newspapers, in the words of our journalists, and in the heart of every Malaysian.

Happy 68th National Day

snippet.title: Indonesia riots: What you need to know
snippet.description:
Indonesia was rocked by violent protests in Jakarta and other major cities on Friday, triggered by anger over the rising cost of living and lawmakers‚Äô lavish perks.

The unrest, fuelled by months of frustration, escalated after a rideshare driver was killed during police action, sparking the deadliest riots in decades.

Protests began on Aug 25 in Jakarta before spreading nationwide, as students, workers, and labour groups demanded tax reforms, higher wages, and an end to outsourcing.

On Aug 27, students stormed the West Kalimantan parliament, while two days later, thousands clashed with police outside the national parliament in Jakarta.

Demonstrations also spread to Surabaya, Medan, Banda Aceh, and other cities.

By Aug 29, riots left at least five dead, with parliament buildings torched, homes attacked, and businesses looted.

On Aug 31, President Prabowo Subianto pledged to cut lawmakers‚Äô benefits to ease tensions, as the military moved to secure the capital and government sites.

snippet.description:

Major earthquakes centred in Malaysia ranged between magnitude 6 and 6.3, with incidents recorded in Sabah in 1923, 1958, 1976 and 2015.

snippet.title: Three men plead guilty to performing in 'djinn worship' video in Batu Pahat
snippet.description:
Three men who went viral in a video allegedly showing elements of djinn worship during a kuda kepang performance in Parit Raja a few days ago, pleaded guilty at the Batu Pahat Syariah Court today for performing a ritual that involved elements of polytheism.

The three, Azman Mohamed Seh, 45; Muhammad Suhail Suttrysono, 35; and Anuar Bandi, 40, entered their guilty pleas as the charges were read before Syariah judge Syazwan Mohd Yusof.

According to the charges, Azman and Muhammad Suhail were accused of performing a deviant ritual that goes against Islamic teachings, while Anuar was charged with abetting in the performance, which contained elements of shirik (polytheism or idolatry).

The act was carried out in an open area in front of a house in Parit Raja between 10pm and 1am on Aug 10 and 11.

Azman, a mechanic, and Muhammad Suhail, a security guard, were charged under Section 3 of the Johor Syariah Criminal Offences Enactment 1997, which carries a fine of up to RM3,000, imprisonment of up to two years, or both.

Anuar, who played the drums during the performance, was charged under Section 43(b) and is subject to the same punishment under Section 3 of the same enactment.

Chief Syariah prosecutor Ahmad Wafi Abdullah led the prosecution, while none of the accused were represented.

snippet.title: Mother and daughter survive landslide as house collapses in KK
snippet.description:
A woman and her teenage daughter survived a landslide that completely destroyed their home in Kampung Kopungit, Kepayan, last night.

The incident occurred around 8.45pm when the house of Molly Antutu, 42, and her daughter, Syamimi, 14, collapsed after a loud thud and slid down a slope. Both managed to crawl out to safety with help from neighbours.

Molly sustained minor leg injuries, while her daughter was unhurt.

Kota Kinabalu Civil Defence Force officer Captain Aizex Junior said the landslide measured about 15 metres wide and 25 metres high. Two other landslides were also detected nearby, and monitoring is ongoing.
